ncreased antibiotic resistance","Limited anterior prostate sampling","Poor cancer detection rate","Requires general anaesthesia"],"correctOptions":[4],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003ETransperineal (TP) prostate biopsy has become increasingly favoured over the traditional transrectal approach due to its lower infection risk and better sampling capabilities. The TP approach has become the preferred method at many centres due to its superior safety profile and sampling capabilities, despite the need for general anaesthesia. Local anaesthetic techniques are being developed but are not yet widely adopted. The main limitation is that \u003Cstrong\u003Egeneral anaesthesia\u003C/strong\u003E is typically required, which increases resource utilisation and procedural complexity.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EPoor cancer detection rate\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as TP biopsy actually has excellent cancer detection rates, particularly for anterior tumours which can be missed by the transrectal approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EHigh risk of sepsis\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as TP biopsy has a significantly lower infection risk compared to transrectal biopsy because it avoids traversing contaminated rectal mucosa.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ELimited anterior prostate sampling\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect as TP biopsy provides superior access to the anterior prostate compared to the transrectal approach.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EIncreased antibiotic resistance\u003C/strong\u003E is incorrect. In fact, TP biopsy requires fewer prophylactic antibiotics than transrectal biopsy, potentially reducing antibiotic resistance risk.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Transperineal prostate biopsy has a lower infection risk compared to transrectal biopsy but requires general anaesthesia.","Transperineal approach allows better sampling of anterior prostate tumours compared to transrectal biopsy.","Urinary retention is a known complication of transperineal prostate biopsy due to prostatic swelling."],"references":["Thomson A, Li M, Grummet J, Sengupta S. Transperineal prostate biopsy: a review of technique. Transl Androl Urol. 2020 Dec;9(6):3009-3017. doi: 10.21037/tau.2019.12.40. PMID: 33457274; PMCID: PMC7807331.","Ortner G, Tzanaki E, Rai BP, Nagele U, Tokas T. Transperineal prostate biopsy: The modern gold standard to prostate cancer diagnosis. Turk J Urol. 2021 Feb;47(Supp. 1):S19-S26. doi: 10.5152/tud.2020.20358. Epub 2020 Oct 9. PMID: 33052837; PMCID: PMC8057359.","Diamand R, Peltier A, Albisinni S. Transrectal prostate biopsy: easy, effective and safe. Prostate Cancer Prostatic Dis. 2024 Sep;27(3):363-364. doi: 10.1038/s41391-024-00823-1. Epub 2024 Apr 16. PMID: 38627538."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51903"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"15146"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"51903","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/itemRevisions/51903"},"attributes":{"createdAt":"2024-11-30T09:44:46+10:30","updatedAt":"2024-11-30T09:45:00+10:30"},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"7834"}},"content":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"66452"}}},"meta":{"canDelete":false}},{"type":"tags","id":"1","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/1"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83d\ude34","name":"Anaesthesia","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{"type":"tagGroups","id":"1"}},"heading":{"data":{"type":"tagHeadings","id":"5"}}},"meta":{"itemCount":0}},{"type":"tags","id":"36","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/tags/36"},"attributes":{"emoji":"\ud83e\udd43","name":"Urology","synonyms":null,"description":null,"position":null,"createdAt":null,"updatedAt":null},"relationships":{"group":{"data":{